Certainly! Below is an example of how you might represent this concept using TikZ in LaTeX. This example will create a grid representing the raster scan order of bits or blocks.

```latex
\documentclass{standalone}
\usepackage{tikz}

\begin{document}

\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=2, every node/.style={draw, fill=white, inner sep=1pt}]

% Define patch size and number of bits/blocks per row/column
\def\n{3} % Patch size (number of bits/block per row/column)

% Draw the grid
\foreach \i in {0,...,\n-1} {
  \foreach \j in {0,...,\n-1} {
    \node at (\i, -\j) {};
  }
}

% Label the nodes with b_i or B_n^i
\foreach \i in {0,...,\n-1} {
  \foreach \j in {0,...,\n-1} {
    \pgfmathsetmacro{\bit}{(\i*\n)+\j+1}
    \node[below right] at (\i, -\j) {$b_{\bit}$};
  }
}

\end{tikzpicture}

\end{document}
```

### Explanation:
- **Grid Creation**: The `\foreach` loops create a grid of nodes. Each node represents a bit or block.
- **Labeling**: Another set of nested `\foreach` loops labels each node with `b_i`, where `i` ranges from 0 to `n*n-1`.

### Customization:
- You can change the value of `\n` to adjust the patch size.
- If you want to label the nodes differently (e.g., `B_n^i`), you can modify the `\pgfmathsetmacro` line accordingly.

This example should give you a good starting point for creating a raster scan order diagram using TikZ in LaTeX. Feel free to ask if you need further customization or additional features!

